[u][b]Methods[/b][/u]

A method is considered as "instructions" for your application and links can be executed by either the main method (usually a start up of a application) or by other methods which may want execute it. Here's an example...

Here I created a method which does a simple job of printing a message "Hello world!"
[code=java]/**
 * Method used to print "Hello World!"
 */
public void myMethod() {
    System.out.println("Hello world!");
}[/code]

Now the method has to be called somewhere otherwise it would just be sitting there doing nothing!
[code=java]/**
 * Main method used to start server
 */
public void main(String[] args) {
    myMethod(); // executes myMethod()
}[/code]

[u][b]Parenthesis
[/b][/u]

Parenthesis is just a posh word for brackets and braces } ( ) 

[b]Braces:[/b]

When you create a class you always have a brace { } to open the class and one to close it.

[code=java]public class Test {

}[/code]

If you miss out a brace you'll most likely get 100 errors whilst compiling.

[code=java]
public class Test {
    private int x;

    private void randomMethod() {
        if (x == 1) {
            System.out.println("x is equal to 1");
    }

}
[/code]

The above method 'randomMethod()' looks fine and won't give us any errors. Will it? If you look at the 1st line of code within that method

[code=java]if (x == 1) {[/code]
we have a open parenthesis but its not closed because we have got a } at the end of the class but that will only close the method or the open variable so we need to make sure we close all statement. You fill up that section with everything you need then close it for example:

[code=java]private void randomMethod() {
    if (x==1) {
        System.out.println("Hello world!"); // if x == 1 print hello world!
        x = 2; // make x = 2
    }
    // anything else which does not relate to x being 1 goes under the }
}[/code]

