[b]Brackets[/b]: 

Everybody should know what a Bracket is but for those who don't its a curly line [b]( )[/b] 

How brackets work is easy and similar to braces except they need to be closed on the same line they where opened.

if (rand == 12 {

}

I have a open bracket within that IF statement but it is UN-closed so after you open a bracket and filled it with the junk you need just close the bracket ) then add the rest of your code after it.

public void example() {
    int rand;
    if (rand == 12) {
        System.out.println("rand is equal to 12");
   }
}

[u][b]Follow up IF and else statements[/b][/u]
An IF statement is literally 

[code]if (...) {

}[/code]

how they work is simple and if you think of it logically its pretty much saying [b]if [/b]something [b]is [/b]something then [b]do [/b]something; for example

[code=java]if (variable == number) {
    doSomething(); // this can be anything from execution and change of values
}[/code]

now to put that into real code it would be like
[code=java]
int random = 12;
public void method() {
    if (random == 12) { // if variable is something (can include bigger and less then)
        random ++; // do something (in this case increase the value)
    }
}[/code]

Else statements are just exactly the same as a IF statement but its more of a carry on of the if statement e.g. if variable is something then do something otherwise/else do this.

Here's an example of what I mean:

[code=java]    int random = 12;

    if (random > 11) {
        System.out.println("Random is currently " + random);
    } else {
        System.out.println("Random is smaller then 12!");
    }[/code]

what that code does is tell us the current value for the variable [b]random[/b] which is currently set to 12. If you do (random > 11) { < what that does is anything above 11 so if the variable was to be 11 the else statement would kick in telling us its smaller then 12 because we did not tell the application to include the 11. We'll get into the inequality signs in a few mins but first here's another example of if statements/else statements.


[code=java]    if (random == 1) {
        System.out.println("random is equal to: 1");
    } else if (random == 2) {
        System.out.println("random is equal to: 2");
    }[/code]

if you've been reading most of what i'm saying the code should litter ally be understandable as it is.
if random is equal to 1, print "random is equal to: 1" otherwise if random is equal to 2, print "random is equal to 2"

Easy? :)

