[u][b]Booleans
[/b][/u]

A boolean is Java's term for on/off (true/false) and it can be applied in methods and you can make switches etc. 

Here's an example of a boolean:
[code]public boolean myMethod() {
    if (rand == 12) {
        executeMethod();
    return true;
    } else {
    return false;
}[/code]

As you can see I declared the method as a boolean instead of a void. what the method does is execute a method IF the variable rand is equal to 12. You MUST have a return statement (yes/no) so under executeMethod() I wrote return true; what that basically means is YES YES YES DO IT! and return false; NO NO NO STOP AND DON'T DO ANYTHING! (simplest way to explain it)

You can also use booleans as an actual switch e.g.
[code=java]
private boolean serverRunning;

public void run() {
    if (serverRunning == true) {
        // what ever you want to run goes here
        serverRunning == true; // Just making sure the switch is set to ON 
        System.out.print("Server is online!"); // gives us the message that server is now running
    } else if (serverRunning == false) {
        System.out.println("Server is ALREADY running!!!!!");// tell us that the server is already running
        serverRunning == false; // makes sure the switch is OFF
        System.exit(0); // close's the server
}[/code]

(may of made a mistake) 


What ^that basically does is stops multipul servers from being ran at one time so if serverRunning is set to true, that means yes it is running and the else statement tells us if the server is already running and closes the one you just attempted to start.


