[u][b]Integers/INTS, BYTE, SHORT, LONG[/b][/u]

Java stores integers in binary numbers (int, byte, short, long)

In Java, the 'int' type is a primitive , whereas the 'Integer' type is an object. The differences between objects and primitives are somewhat beyond the my noob intelligence, but to summarize, objects provide facilities for polymorphism, are passed by reference (or more accurately have references passed by value), and are allocated from the heap. Conversely, primitives are immutable types that are passed by value and are often allocated from the stack.

Did you understand that ^? Probably not. There will be a list of words followed by a definition at the bottom of this tutorial soon enough. 

Here is a rough idea of what the different data types are

[b]byte [/b]is made up of 8 bits (size) and it can range from -128 to 127.
So a byte is made up of 8 bits, quiet similar to a MEGABYTE (MB) where in MB there are 8388608 bits.

A [b]short [/b]has 2 bytes (16 bits) and it can range from -32,768 to +32,767
and it literally starts to double from here,

[b]int [/b]made up of 4 bytes	(32 bits) ranges from	-2,147,483,648 to	+2,147,483,647
[b]long [/b]made up of	8 bytes (64 bits) ranges from	-9,223,372,036,854,775,808 to	+9,223,372,036,854,775,80

Bits are the smallest possible data type.

Ints are commonly used maybe because it holds enough information and its easy to type? :P

private int value1; // a int which is named value1 (this is also a variable because the value can be changed!)

value1 == 2; // defines value1 as a 2
value1 +=1; // increases value1 by 1 so if values 1 was 2 for example; value1 would increase to 3


[u][b]Switch Statements[/b][/u]

A switch statement looks somewhat like this:

[code=java]switch(variable) {
    case 1:
       System.out.println("Hello MOPAR!");
      break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Hello World!");
      break;
    }
}[/code]

Switch statement is a tidier way of doing if/else if statements!

Here's a chunk of code quickly made so you guys can relate it to your RSPS.

[code=java]private void commands(Player player, String command) {
    if (command[0].equals("update")) {
        // send update
    }
    if (command[0].equals("master")) {
        // give player max stats
    }
}[/code]

That code can also be written like so:

[code=java]private void commands(Player player, String command) {
    if (command[0].equals("update")) {
        // send update
    } else if (command[0].equals("master")) {
        // give player max stats
    }
}[/code]

To make a switch statement you put the crap that would go in within the IF statement and put it into a switch statement like this:

[code]switch (command) {
    case"update":
      //send update
      break;
    case"master":
      //give player max stats
      break;
}[/code]

You must make sure you have a colon after the case (case"test":) and don't forget to add [b]break; [/b]

Another cool thing about switch statements are you can stack things example:

[b]case"master":
case"max":
maxstats();
 break;[/b]

What that does is if the the command is called master or max it will still give execute the same command without needing to retype it or do any special operations.

[u][b]Loops[/b][/u]

What is a loop? A loop is something which keeps going and does not stop a bit like a circle lol? 

[code=java]public void loop() {
    while (true) {
        System.out.println("LOOPPING!");
    }
}[/code]

That above code will just SPAM LOOPING! a million times until you stop the application!
Loops are usually used in processes that are not to be stopped such as networking, having a process after x seconds etc etc

You can use a boolean also for looping e.g. 

[code=java]boolean loop = true; // the on/off switch for the loop

while (loop) {
 // crap goes here
}
[/code]

[u][b]Generics[/b][/u]
When a class is defined with the parameter (or parameters) then it’s called as Parameterized class. It’s another name for generic class. The parameter is called as Type parameter.

Here's an example:

[code=java]public class PTest<E> extends ArrayList<E> {
   //stuff goes here
}[/code]

The above class PTest is parameterized with one parameter type ‘E’’ but it can have more than one parameter. Type parameter is an unqualified identifier that is used as a place holder. This will be replaced by the compiler with the specified Type when an object is created for the generic class. 

Instanciation where the parameter is replaced with an Integer
[code]PTest <Integer> ptest= new PTest<Integer> ();[/code]

You can also do:

[code=java]public class First<T> extends Second<String> implements Runnable<String> {

   @Override
   public void run() {
       //TODO:
   }
}[/code]

