[b][u]Enum[/b][/u]

What is a Enum? 
Enum is type like class and interface and can be used to define a set of Enum constants. Enum constants are implicitly static and final and you can not change there value once created. Enum in Java provides type-safety and can be used inside switch statment like int variables.

Here's an example:
[code=java]public enum STATE{ LOGIN, HANDSHAKE, REQUEST }[/code]

You can add it within a switch statement too like with any primitive types such as ints;
[code]   switch (state) {
            case REQUEST:
                    System.out.println("Request");
                    break;
            case HANDSHAKE:
                    System.out.println("Handshake");
                    break;
            case LOGIN:
                    System.out.println("Login");
                    break;
    }[/code]

Enum type is a data type that enables for a variable to be a set of predefined constants. The variable must be equal to one of the values that have been predefined for it. 
You should use Enum whenever you need to represent a fixed set of constants

And for those who don't know what a constant is, its basically something that does not change! For Enum it's basically a set of conditions which it will always follow whatever the variables must be. If that makes any sense :S

[u][b]Parameters[/b][/u] - reference from mindprod.org
A parameter is a variable that you pass in to a function. Kinda like an argument...only not as loud and frustrating.

Parameters are always passed by value not by reference. The called method gets a copy of each primitive and a copy of the pointer to each object. The called method can therefore not change any local variables in the caller. However it can change the contents of objects (which includes strings and arrays) passed to it. Some people may argue that counts as call by reference, however a calle cannot make the callers variables point to different objects, just change the contents of objects. Objects are always accessed by reference, (literally via a reference) even when parameters are not involved. You can kludge call by reference by passing values back to your caller inside an array or by returning a freshly minted object full of values.

[code=java]/**
 * add two numbers
 * @param a first addend
 * @param b second addend
 * @return sum of a+b
 */
static int add( int a, int b )
   {
   // a and b are 'parameters', the variables the callee uses to accept inputs.
   return a + b;
   }
[/code]

It's sort of similar to having a variable declared but in this case its for a sole method only.




[u][size=12pt]Starting your own Java application? [/size][/u]

In this part of the tutorial I'll be showing you some cool tips and tricks alongside most of the information you need to know when creating your own crap.

I would recommend you read up on Java docs by Oracle since it will help you out (its not very graphically friendly sadly :( )

When you first start building an application/server you'll always need a MAIN method that will literally hold all your start up processes.
Main methods are created like so:

[code=java]public static void main(String[] args) {
    // all your stuff goes here
}[/code]

making sure all your methods link up etc etc is vital because if you create a method that's not being called anywhere; you'll be stuck with it being unused and wasting space.

Here's a quick example of a basic application:

[code=java]public class Server {
    private int moparscape;
    private int runeServer;
    private int google;

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        init();
    }

    private boolean init() {
        if (runeServer && google > moparscape) {
            System.out.println("Something went wrong here....");
        return false;
    } else if (moparscape > google || runeServer) {
        System.out.println("You are on the correct path of learning to program!");
        moparscape++;
        return true;
    }

}[/code]

^ my quick crappy code (not going to explain what it does lol) but as you can see I have my variables declared, methods created, main method created, my methods are being called and it should run perfectly fine :)



[b]Some cools things you can try out...[/b]

[code=java]
/**
 * Define the TimerTask class (already comes with Java)
 */
private TimerTask t;

public void sayHello() {
     if (System.currentTimeMillis() - t.scheduledExecutionTime() >= 5) { // code to scheduled an execution time
         System.out.println("Its been 5 seconds now: HELLO!!!!"); // print message
     }

}[/code]

What the method does is, give a 5 second delay before doing what ever in my case saying HELLO!!!! (untested just assuming)

Another way to add a delay is Thread.sleep(x);
Its literally the same thing as scheduledExecutionTime but add a ms delay so the process completely freezes e.g.

     thread.sleep(1000); // code to scheduled an execution time
         System.out.println("Its been 5 seconds now: HELLO!!!!"); // print message
     }

for sleep(); it works with milliseconds so 1000 ms == 1 second

